<paragraph id="935036FBFFBAFFFB45F8445BFD39FB87" blockId="10.[212,1172,1025,1113]" box="[212,672,1025,1050]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">
<heading id="C8188197FFBAFFFB45F8445BFD39FB87" box="[212,672,1025,1050]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609" reason="5">
<taxonomicName id="54EF4D78FFBAFFFB45F8445BFDC9FB87" authority="Wood 1910, p. 150" authorityName="Wood" authorityPageNumber="150" authorityYear="1910" box="[212,592,1025,1050]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Phora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serrata">
<emphasis id="A19BEAE9FFBAFFFB45F8445BFEF4FB87" box="[212,365,1026,1050]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Phora serrata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="F77E4B0AFFBAFFFB445A4458FE60FB87" author="Wood JH" box="[374,505,1025,1049]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609" pagination="243 - 249" refId="ref8850" refString="Wood JH. 1910. On the British species of Phora (contd). Entomol Mon Mag. 46: 149 - 154, 195 - 202, 243 - 249." type="journal article" year="1910">Wood 1910</bibRefCitation>
, p. 150
</taxonomicName>
(male)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="935036FBFFBAFFFB45D04478FD4BFBC7" blockId="10.[212,1172,1025,1113]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">
The male of this species is covered by the key to British species (
<bibRefCitation id="F77E4B0AFFBAFFFB46EA4478FBC8FBA7" author="Disney RHL" box="[966,1105,1057,1081]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref8043" refString="Disney RHL. 1989. Scuttle Flies - Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbk Ident Br Insects. 10: 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
). The hitherto-unknown female is described below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DBF56570FFBAFFFC45F844C4FC02FB7F" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="1612" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609" type="description">
<paragraph id="935036FBFFBAFFFB45F844C4FEBDFB2B" blockId="10.[212,1173,1181,1691]" box="[212,292,1181,1205]" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">
<heading id="C8188197FFBAFFFB45F844C4FEBDFB2B" box="[212,292,1181,1205]" fontSize="10" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609" reason="5">
<emphasis id="A19BEAE9FFBAFFFB45F844C4FEBDFB2B" box="[212,292,1181,1205]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Female</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="935036FBFFBAFFFC45F8449CFC02FB7F" blockId="10.[212,1173,1181,1691]" lastBlockId="13.[144,1105,1066,1249]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="1612" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">
Head similar to male but the greyish-brown labrum is 1.1–1.2 times as wide as the diameter of the postpedicel (which, like that of the male, lacks subcutaneous pit sensilla [SPS] vesicles). In the male, the labrum is only about 0.08 times as wide as a postpedicel. Labella paler, with submarginal light brown bands above and very few bristles reduced to small spinules below at tips. Otherwise head similar to male. Thorax similar to male, in having three bristles on notopleuron, seven to 10 hairs on mesopleuron, and scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown and as in 
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB45F8459DFEDEFA42" box="[212,327,1476,1500]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="11.[144,211,823,845]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,791]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[144,1104,168,791]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 9. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, tergites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006334/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Figures 9</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB44A1459DFE30FA42" box="[397,425,1476,1500]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="11.[144,211,1666,1688]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,915,1635]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[144,1104,915,1635]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 10. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, tergites 7–10." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006336" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006336/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">10</figureCitation>
. Terminal segments as in 
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB47D4459DFCF6FA42" box="[760,879,1476,1500]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="12.[212,279,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,1000,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[212,1172,1000,1690]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 12. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, sternite 7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006340/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Figure 12</figureCitation>
. Venter grey, and with hairs below segments 3–6. Sternite 7 brown and as in 
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB464645BDFC47FA62" box="[874,990,1508,1532]" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="12.[212,279,1722,1744]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,1000,1690]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[212,1172,1000,1690]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 12. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, sternite 7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006340" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006340/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Figure 12</figureCitation>
. Posterolateral lobes at rear of sternum 8 tinged brown and with three hairs at rear margin and several smaller ones further forward (
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB47E9467AFCD8F9A5" box="[709,833,1571,1595]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="13.[144,211,993,1015]" captionTargetBox="[144,1104,168,961]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[144,1104,168,961]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 13. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, lobes at rear of sternum 8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006342" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006342/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Figure 13</figureCitation>
). Cerci brown and as in 
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB45F8461AFED2F9C5" box="[212,331,1603,1627]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="12.[212,279,920,942]" captionTargetBox="[212,1172,168,888]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[212,1172,168,888]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 11. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, terminal segments from above." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006338" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4006338/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Figure 11</figureCitation>
. Furca pale grey and outline variable in relation to angle of view (
<figureCitation id="0BD42A7EFFBAFFFB45F1463AFE10F9E5" box="[221,393,1635,1659]" captionStart-0="Figure 14" captionStart-1="Figure 15" captionStart-2="Figure 16" captionStartId-0="14.[212,279,1100,1122]" captionStartId-1="15.[144,211,697,719]" captionStartId-2="15.[143,210,1480,1502]" captionTargetBox-0="[212,1172,153,1068]" captionTargetBox-1="[144,1104,168,665]" captionTargetBox-2="[143,1103,781,1448]" captionTargetId-0="figure@14.[212,1172,153,1068]" captionTargetId-1="figure@15.[144,1104,168,665]" captionTargetId-2="figure@15.[143,1103,781,1448]" captionTargetPageId-0="14" captionTargetPageId-1="15" captionTargetPageId-2="15" captionText-0="Figure 14. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, furca." captionText-1="Figure 15. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, furca from a second specimen." captionText-2="Figure 16. Megaselia serrata female, details of abdomen, furca from a third specimen." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006344" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006346" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4006348" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4006344/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4006346/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/4006348/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="1609">Figures 14–16</figureCitation>
). Dufour’ s crop mechanism seemingly absent. Legs similar to male but the hind femur lacks the hooked spines beneath the basal half, where the hairs are subequal to the anteroventral hairs of the distal half. The dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia, as in male, extends about two thirds of length. Wing as male except 
<quantity id="54179B1EFFBDFFFC44754433FE70FB1F" box="[345,489,1130,1154]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="13" pageNumber="1612" unit="mm" value="1.45" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.4">1.4–1.5 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.40. Costal ratios 4.4:1.7:1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity id="54179B1EFFBDFFFC44E244D3FDAFFB3F" box="[462,566,1162,1186]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7" pageId="13" pageNumber="1612" unit="mm" value="0.07">0.07 mm</quantity>
long. Vein Sc not reaching vein 1 and with no hair at base of vein 3. With two unequal axillary bristles, the outer being longer than the costal cilia. Otherwise wing and haltere as male.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
